where your application
schedules this notification

00:03:11.076 --> 00:03:13.206 A:middle
with the system showing
the notification

00:03:13.206 --> 00:03:16.026 A:middle
to the user's device, and
when the user handles this

00:03:16.026 --> 00:03:18.586 A:middle
notification, your
application gets a callback.

00:03:19.986 --> 00:03:21.346 A:middle
As I mentioned, examples

00:03:21.346 --> 00:03:23.506 A:middle
of these can include
task reminder alerts,

00:03:23.906 --> 00:03:26.006 A:middle
calendar alerts, or
location based triggers.

00:03:27.376 --> 00:03:30.316 A:middle
Now, not all your
applications are contained

00:03:30.506 --> 00:03:31.516 A:middle
on the user's device.

00:03:32.126 --> 00:03:35.016 A:middle
A lot of them have a
server-side component as well,

00:03:35.016 --> 00:03:37.076 A:middle
where your server-side
application lives

00:03:37.426 --> 00:03:39.126 A:middle
across the network
on your servers.

00:03:39.906 --> 00:03:41.786 A:middle
So to facilitate notifications

00:03:41.786 --> 00:03:43.986 A:middle
for that we have
remote notifications.

00:03:44.606 --> 00:03:46.426 A:middle
Let's take a look at how
remote notifications work.

00:03:47.536 --> 00:03:50.946 A:middle
The main piece involved in
this exchange is the Apple Push

00:03:50.946 --> 00:03:53.256 A:middle
Notification Service,
or APNs for short.

00:03:54.386 --> 00:03:55.706 A:middle
It's part of remote
notifications.

00:03:56.496 --> 00:03:59.026 A:middle
Your remote site application
sends the notification payload

00:03:59.186 --> 00:04:02.426 A:middle
to APNs, which then does
a best-effort delivery

00:03:59.186 --> 00:04:02.426 A:middle
to APNs, which then does
a best-effort delivery

00:04:02.586 --> 00:04:05.386 A:middle
of this notification to the
user's device, showing them

00:04:05.386 --> 00:04:07.936 A:middle
that notification and then
forwarding your application

00:04:07.936 --> 00:04:11.226 A:middle
to be handled when the
user interacts with it.

00:04:11.496 --> 00:04:14.606 A:middle
Examples of remote notifications
can be news alerts,

00:04:14.656 --> 00:04:17.616 A:middle
where your server-side
application gets the latest

00:04:17.616 --> 00:04:20.805 A:middle
breaking news and then
forwards all these notifications

00:04:20.956 --> 00:04:23.386 A:middle
to the different devices
on all the clients

00:04:23.576 --> 00:04:26.436 A:middle
that have your application
installed on their device.

00:04:27.606 --> 00:04:30.176 A:middle
Instant messaging alerts as well
where the database is managed

00:04:30.176 --> 00:04:33.186 A:middle
on your servers, and when a new
message comes in you just pass

00:04:33.186 --> 00:04:35.236 A:middle
that notification along
to the user's device.

00:04:36.976 --> 00:04:40.896 A:middle
Now remote notifications in turn
have two different components,

00:04:41.216 --> 00:04:43.636 A:middle
they can be either
user-facing or silent updates.

00:04:44.216 --> 00:04:46.136 A:middle
Now user-facing notifications,

00:04:46.136 --> 00:04:48.576 A:middle
