you need a network connection so
that the system can then go talk

00:11:53.726 --> 00:11:55.586 A:middle
to APNs for this registration

00:11:55.586 --> 00:11:57.106 A:middle
for your device and
your application.

00:11:58.306 --> 00:12:00.816 A:middle
This token gets returned to
your client-side application,

00:11:58.306 --> 00:12:00.816 A:middle
This token gets returned to
your client-side application,

00:12:01.096 --> 00:12:02.256 A:middle
which then you need to forward

00:12:02.256 --> 00:12:03.606 A:middle
to your servicer-side
application.

00:12:04.336 --> 00:12:07.216 A:middle
Now this is important because
this token needs to be included

00:12:07.216 --> 00:12:09.066 A:middle
as part of the notification
payload

00:12:09.356 --> 00:12:11.396 A:middle
that your remote side
application is passing

00:12:11.396 --> 00:12:12.036 A:middle
through your APNs.

00:12:12.776 --> 00:12:16.466 A:middle
Because this token acts as the
key for identifying your device

00:12:16.656 --> 00:12:19.266 A:middle
and the application to which it
wants to send the notification.

00:12:21.256 --> 00:12:22.616 A:middle
So that was registration.

00:12:22.886 --> 00:12:24.406 A:middle
Now your application is ready

00:12:24.406 --> 00:12:26.446 A:middle
to start sending
notifications to the users.

00:12:26.876 --> 00:12:27.996 A:middle
So the first thing
that you need to do

00:12:27.996 --> 00:12:31.276 A:middle
after that is create the
content of that notification.

00:12:33.276 --> 00:12:36.206 A:middle
Now I'm sure all of you have
seen the brand new notification

00:12:36.206 --> 00:12:38.216 A:middle
looks that we've
introduced with iOS X.

00:12:38.656 --> 00:12:41.496 A:middle
We're really excited about
what this allows you to do.

00:12:42.046 --> 00:12:45.266 A:middle
To start with, we now show the
title of your notifications

00:12:45.356 --> 00:12:46.966 A:middle
in all iOS notifications.

00:12:47.516 --> 00:12:51.216 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:12:51.716 --> 00:12:53.866 A:middle
We've also included an
extra field for the subtitle

00:12:53.866 --> 00:12:55.586 A:middle
so you can have more
dexterity in the type

00:12:55.586 --> 00:12:57.236 A:middle
of information you're
sending to the user.

00:12:58.066 --> 00:13:00.126 A:middle
And of course, there's
the body of the content.

00:12:58.066 --> 00:13:00.126 A:middle
And of course, there's
the body of the content.

00:13:00.916 --> 00:13:03.606 A:middle
Let's take a look at how
to set this up in code.

00:13:05.276 --> 00:13:08.796 A:middle
So it's as simple as creating
a UNmutableNotificationContent

00:13:08.796 --> 00:13:11.806 A:middle
object and setting the different
properties on it, that's it.

00:13:13.036 --> 00:13:15.276 A:middle
For remote notifications,
it's fairly similar.

00:13:15.766 --> 00:13:17.926 A:middle
Your notification payload
is structured as shown here,

00:13:17.926 --> 00:13:19.916 A:middle
and again you set the
different properties

00:13:19.916 --> 00:13:24.276 A:middle
of your payload before
sending it to APNs.

00:13:25.516 --> 00:13:26.986 A:middle
However, that's not
it for content,

00:13:27.246 --> 00:13:29.636 A:middle
we decided to go one step
further, and starting

00:13:29.636 --> 00:13:33.086 A:middle
in iOS X we now let all
applications do media

00:13:33.086 --> 00:13:34.946 A:middle
attachments right in
the notifications.

00:13:35.516 --> 00:13:39.586 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:13:40.086 --> 00:13:41.406 A:middle
So now you can have much richer

00:13:41.626 --> 00:13:44.336 A:middle
and colorful notifications
that your users see.

00:13:45.176 --> 00:13:47.966 A:middle
For more on media attachments,
we'll be doing a walkthrough

00:13:47.966 --> 00:13:50.456 A:middle
on how to set these up in the
Advance Notifications Session.

00:13:52.356 --> 00:13:55.336 A:middle
So now that your content
is ready, the next thing

00:13:55.336 --> 00:13:57.596 A:middle
that your app needs to
determine is when it wants

00:13:57.596 --> 00:13:58.516 A:middle
to send the notification.

00:13:58.966 --> 00:14:00.656 A:middle
And for that there are triggers.

00:13:58.966 --> 00:14:00.656 A:middle
And for that there are triggers.

00:14:02.196 --> 00:14:05.616 A:middle
In iOS X we support four
different triggers, mainly push,

00:14:05.956 --> 00:14:08.766 A:middle
timer interval, calendar,
and location based triggers.

00:14:09.346 --> 00:14:13.006 A:middle
Now the push trigger is
associated exclusively

00:14:13.076 --> 00:14:14.296 A:middle
with remote notifications

00:14:14.596 --> 00:14:16.376 A:middle
when your remote side
notification sends the

00:14:16.376 --> 00:14:19.776 A:middle
notification to APNs it
arrives on the device associated

00:14:19.776 --> 00:14:22.766 A:middle
with the push trigger, all the
other triggers are the ones

00:14:23.016 --> 00:14:24.716 A:middle
that are associated with
local notifications.

00:14:27.236 --> 00:14:30.216 A:middle
Now, time interval based
triggers lets you schedule a

00:14:30.216 --> 00:14:32.926 A:middle
notification at a certain time
interval starting from now.

00:14:33.436 --> 00:14:35.486 A:middle
For example, if you wanted
to send the notification

00:14:35.486 --> 00:14:36.416 A:middle
in two minutes from now,

00:14:36.876 --> 00:14:39.696 A:middle
or you want to send it every
hour starting from now.

00:14:40.546 --> 00:14:42.946 A:middle
This also lets you schedule
the notification immediately

00:14:42.946 --> 00:14:44.416 A:middle
by setting the time
interval to zero.

00:14:46.256 --> 00:14:48.526 A:middle
Now as opposed to time interval
based triggers there are

00:14:48.526 --> 00:14:51.486 A:middle
calendar triggers that
lets you set a notification

00:14:51.626 --> 00:14:53.786 A:middle
at a specific date and
time in the future.

00:14:53.856 --> 00:14:56.016 A:middle
So you have more
control of exactly

00:14:56.016 --> 00:14:57.206 A:middle
when the notification gets sent.

00:14:58.296 --> 00:15:01.066 A:middle
Example of this can be at a
certain time tomorrow morning

00:14:58.296 --> 00:15:01.066 A:middle
Example of this can be at a
certain time tomorrow morning

00:15:01.366 --> 00:15:06.136 A:middle
or repeating it on a certain day
of the week at a certain time.

00:15:06.306 --> 00:15:08.716 A:middle
And lastly in triggers, we
have location based triggers,

00:15:09.096 --> 00:15:12.486 A:middle
which uses your devices absolute
location, or its location

00:15:12.486 --> 00:15:15.666 A:middle
in relation to Bluetooth
beacons and determining

00:15:15.666 --> 00:15:16.636 A:middle
if your device is entering

00:15:16.636 --> 00:15:19.066 A:middle
or leaving the region you can
send notification to the user.

00:15:20.116 --> 00:15:23.206 A:middle
Examples of this is when the
user is leaving their home

00:15:23.206 --> 00:15:25.346 A:middle
and the device is
leaving that proximity,

00:15:25.666 --> 00:15:27.516 A:middle
or say that the user
is at a grocery store

00:15:27.556 --> 00:15:28.746 A:middle
and your application wants

00:15:28.746 --> 00:15:30.186 A:middle
to send them a coupon
for a discount.

00:15:31.696 --> 00:15:34.516 A:middle
So those are the different
triggers that we have as part

00:15:34.516 --> 00:15:35.266 A:middle
of this new framework.

00:15:36.216 --> 00:15:38.706 A:middle
Now that your content's ready
and you know when you want

00:15:38.706 --> 00:15:39.706 A:middle
to send the notification,

00:15:40.086 --> 00:15:42.736 A:middle
the next step left is
scheduling the notification

00:15:42.786 --> 00:15:43.366 A:middle
with the system.

00:15:44.816 --> 00:15:49.196 A:middle
For local notifications this is
as simple as calling addrequest

00:15:49.276 --> 00:15:51.296 A:middle
on the UUserNotificationCenter
object.

00:15:52.076 --> 00:15:54.476 A:middle
Which then on the trigger
the system then displays the

00:15:54.476 --> 00:15:55.606 A:middle
notification to the user.

00:15:56.626 --> 00:15:58.406 A:middle
And for remote notifications,

00:16:00.216 --> 00:16:03.196 A:middle
your service-side application
passes the payload to APNs,

00:16:03.506 --> 00:16:05.336 A:middle
which does a best effort
delivery sending the

00:16:05.336 --> 00:16:07.176 A:middle
notification to the
user's device.

00:16:08.466 --> 00:16:10.366 A:middle
So let's summarize this
whole delivery mechanism

00:16:10.426 --> 00:16:12.026 A:middle
that we've talked about so far.

00:16:12.956 --> 00:16:15.846 A:middle
Your application starts out by
registering with the system.

00:16:16.816 --> 00:16:20.356 A:middle
Then it creates the content,
determines when it wants

00:16:20.356 --> 00:16:21.406 A:middle
to send the notification

00:16:21.936 --> 00:16:23.486 A:middle
and finally schedules
the notification

00:16:23.486 --> 00:16:24.766 A:middle
with the system leading

00:16:24.766 --> 00:16:27.336 A:middle
to the notification getting
shown to the user's device.

00:16:27.446 --> 00:16:28.256 A:middle
It's as simple as that.

00:16:29.516 --> 00:16:31.236 A:middle
Let's take a look at
the summary in code.

00:16:32.426 --> 00:16:35.996 A:middle
Start out by doing registration,
by calling requestAuthorization,

00:16:37.076 --> 00:16:39.066 A:middle
you create the content
of that notification.

00:16:39.116 --> 00:16:43.466 A:middle
You create the trigger, in this
example a simple time interval

00:16:43.466 --> 00:16:46.666 A:middle
based trigger, and then
you package all of this

00:16:46.706 --> 00:16:49.466 A:middle
in a UNNotificationRequest
object,

00:16:49.666 --> 00:16:51.106 A:middle
passing a unique identifier,

00:16:51.666 --> 00:16:53.216 A:middle
which will be important
we will talk

00:16:53.216 --> 00:16:54.036 A:middle
about later in this session.

00:16:54.856 --> 00:16:57.486 A:middle
And then you schedule this
notification with the system,

00:16:58.236 --> 00:16:59.936 A:middle
completing the notification's
delivery.

00:17:02.716 --> 00:17:04.596 A:middle
So, so far we've talked
about what happens

00:17:04.596 --> 00:17:07.146 A:middle
to a notification while your
app is in the background

00:17:07.306 --> 00:17:08.886 A:middle
and the user's not
interacting with it,

00:17:09.026 --> 00:17:11.165 A:middle
but what if your application
is in the foreground

00:17:11.205 --> 00:17:12.965 A:middle
when it receives a notification?

00:17:13.695 --> 00:17:15.386 A:middle
And for this we do offer support

00:17:15.556 --> 00:17:17.756 A:middle
for notification handling while
your app is in the foreground.

00:17:19.146 --> 00:17:19.945 A:middle
Your application needs

00:17:19.945 --> 00:17:22.096 A:middle
to implement the
UNUserNotificationCenter

00:17:22.096 --> 00:17:22.586 A:middle
delegate.

00:17:23.185 --> 00:17:25.556 A:middle
And it has a method of
willPresent notification,

00:17:25.906 --> 00:17:28.726 A:middle
which lets you get the
notification content as part

00:17:28.726 --> 00:17:32.016 A:middle
of the UNNotification object
passed with this method.

00:17:32.896 --> 00:17:34.886 A:middle
Now this method also
has a CompletionHandler,

00:17:35.006 --> 00:17:36.816 A:middle
which must be called at
the end of this function.

00:17:38.116 --> 00:17:40.486 A:middle
One thing to note is that
the CompletionHandler takes

00:17:40.666 --> 00:17:42.126 A:middle
presentation options parameters.

00:17:43.446 --> 00:17:46.026 A:middle
Now, what this enables you to
do is the in-app presentation

00:17:46.026 --> 00:17:47.036 A:middle
that we talked about earlier.

00:17:48.026 --> 00:17:50.386 A:middle
Let's see an example of how
you can configure it up.

00:17:51.476 --> 00:17:55.516 A:middle
So, say your application still
wants to show the user the view

00:17:55.746 --> 00:17:57.996 A:middle
as well as your sound alert
while your application is

00:17:57.996 --> 00:17:58.566 A:middle
in foreground.

00:17:58.856 --> 00:18:01.196 A:middle
So this is as simple as
calling the handler block

00:17:58.856 --> 00:18:01.196 A:middle
So this is as simple as
calling the handler block

00:18:01.286 --> 00:18:02.606 A:middle
with these different parameters.

00:18:03.346 --> 00:18:04.896 A:middle
And if you don't want
in-app presentation,

00:18:04.896 --> 00:18:06.306 A:middle
you just don't pass
any parameters.

00:18:07.176 --> 00:18:10.136 A:middle
So that was notification
handling while your application

00:18:10.136 --> 00:18:11.376 A:middle
is in foreground.

00:18:11.936 --> 00:18:14.816 A:middle
Let's move on and talk about
notification management.

00:18:15.696 --> 00:18:18.016 A:middle
Now notification management
is new with this framework

00:18:18.346 --> 00:18:22.426 A:middle
and what this allows you to do
is have access to notification

00:18:22.506 --> 00:18:23.936 A:middle
that are pending delivery

00:18:23.936 --> 00:18:27.166 A:middle
for your locally scheduled
notifications, as well as access

00:18:27.166 --> 00:18:28.306 A:middle
to delivered notification

00:18:28.626 --> 00:18:31.016 A:middle
that the user might
never see while local

00:18:31.016 --> 00:18:32.146 A:middle
or remove notifications.

00:18:32.816 --> 00:18:34.796 A:middle
Now you can also
remove notifications

00:18:34.796 --> 00:18:38.096 A:middle
that have already been sent
to the user, as well as update

00:18:38.096 --> 00:18:39.486 A:middle
and promote these notifications.

00:18:40.036 --> 00:18:41.996 A:middle
And important piece

00:18:41.996 --> 00:18:44.696 A:middle
of notification management
is the request identifier.

00:18:45.566 --> 00:18:49.596 A:middle
Now, in the summary you saw that
the request identifier is set

00:18:49.596 --> 00:18:51.156 A:middle
on the notification
of the request object.

00:18:51.696 --> 00:18:54.846 A:middle
And for remote notifications
there's a new request header the

00:18:54.846 --> 00:18:57.816 A:middle
APNs collapse id that you
need to set on your payload.

00:18:58.936 --> 00:19:01.216 A:middle
The system uses this
request identifier to know

00:18:58.936 --> 00:19:01.216 A:middle
The system uses this
request identifier to know

00:19:01.216 --> 00:19:03.326 A:middle
which notification
you're requesting

00:19:03.326 --> 00:19:04.556 A:middle
to be removed or updated.

00:19:05.746 --> 00:19:06.356 A:middle
Let's take a look

00:19:06.356 --> 00:19:08.156 A:middle
at notification management
with an example.

00:19:09.326 --> 00:19:12.366 A:middle
Say your application wants to
send notifications for a game,

00:19:12.756 --> 00:19:13.936 A:middle
and it wants to send
notifications

00:19:13.936 --> 00:19:15.016 A:middle
for the start time of the game.

00:19:15.886 --> 00:19:19.196 A:middle
So you start out by creating
your UNNotification request

00:19:20.336 --> 00:19:21.706 A:middle
and scheduling it
with the system,

00:19:22.156 --> 00:19:23.526 A:middle
but say that the
game was cancelled.

00:19:23.906 --> 00:19:27.266 A:middle
So this is as simple as calling
removePendingNotification

00:19:27.266 --> 00:19:30.676 A:middle
Request, passing it the
exact same game identifier

00:19:30.676 --> 00:19:32.586 A:middle
that you created for the
initial notification.

00:19:33.776 --> 00:19:35.656 A:middle
But what if the game
time was updated?

00:19:36.426 --> 00:19:38.546 A:middle
Then you create a new request,

00:19:39.256 --> 00:19:40.746 A:middle
giving it the exact
same identifier

00:19:40.746 --> 00:19:44.666 A:middle
for the initial request,
setting the new trigger time

00:19:45.326 --> 00:19:46.786 A:middle
and just scheduling
it with the system.

00:19:47.386 --> 00:19:49.646 A:middle
And this in turn leads to
updating that notification.

00:19:50.126 --> 00:19:54.136 A:middle
Let's continue this example
for delivered notifications

00:19:54.386 --> 00:19:56.216 A:middle
and talk about score updates.

00:19:57.496 --> 00:19:58.306 A:middle
Again, you just start

00:19:58.306 --> 00:20:00.476 A:middle
out by creating this
notification request

00:19:58.306 --> 00:20:00.476 A:middle
out by creating this
notification request

00:20:01.386 --> 00:20:02.566 A:middle
and sending it to the system.

00:20:03.456 --> 00:20:05.326 A:middle
But say that the wrong
score was updated,

00:20:06.466 --> 00:20:08.696 A:middle
then you can simple
remove that notification

00:20:08.786 --> 00:20:10.656 A:middle
by calling
removeDeliveredNotification

00:20:11.146 --> 00:20:12.716 A:middle
giving it the same identifier.

00:20:14.636 --> 00:20:16.656 A:middle
And what if the score
gets updated

00:20:16.656 --> 00:20:18.596 A:middle
which of course is a very
common case for games.

00:20:19.366 --> 00:20:21.796 A:middle
So all you can do in
this scenario is create a

00:20:21.796 --> 00:20:25.076 A:middle
notification request, giving
it the same identifier,

00:20:25.946 --> 00:20:27.626 A:middle
passing it the new
score content,

00:20:27.986 --> 00:20:30.276 A:middle
and then simply scheduling
it with the system.

00:20:31.676 --> 00:20:34.246 A:middle
Now, what this means, let's
take a look at it as an example,

00:20:34.516 --> 00:20:36.556 A:middle
say that notification
was already there

00:20:36.646 --> 00:20:37.776 A:middle
for initial score update.

00:20:38.456 --> 00:20:41.946 A:middle
So by calling update, as I
showed in code, what this leads

00:20:41.946 --> 00:20:45.346 A:middle
to is that that notification
gets updated right

00:20:45.346 --> 00:20:46.446 A:middle
in the notification list,

00:20:46.686 --> 00:20:48.176 A:middle
replacing the original
notification,

00:20:48.516 --> 00:20:51.206 A:middle
so that you're not cluttering
the user's notification list

00:20:51.206 --> 00:20:51.526 A:middle
at all.

00:20:52.516 --> 00:20:58.006 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:20:58.506 --> 00:21:01.536 A:middle
And you can use this in multiple
ways for aggregating information

00:20:58.506 --> 00:21:01.536 A:middle
And you can use this in multiple
ways for aggregating information

00:21:01.896 --> 00:21:03.196 A:middle
that is right for
your applications.

00:21:04.246 --> 00:21:05.686 A:middle
So that was notification
management,

00:21:05.926 --> 00:21:08.426 A:middle
it really gives your
applications a lot of control

00:21:08.686 --> 00:21:10.936 A:middle
on the notifications that
have been sent to the user.

00:21:12.126 --> 00:21:13.646 A:middle
So so far in this
session we've talked

00:21:13.646 --> 00:21:16.136 A:middle
about how your application
sends these notifications

00:21:16.136 --> 00:21:16.726 A:middle
to the users.

00:21:17.196 --> 00:21:19.246 A:middle
But what about the other
side of this exchange?

00:21:19.816 --> 00:21:22.386 A:middle
Notifications are very
intractable in the form

00:21:22.386 --> 00:21:24.576 A:middle
of default actions as
well as custom actions

00:21:24.646 --> 00:21:26.656 A:middle
that your applications
can set on them.

00:21:27.416 --> 00:21:30.506 A:middle
So, to talk about notification
actions let me invite my

00:21:30.506 --> 00:21:32.576 A:middle
colleague Julien to
continue this session.

00:21:32.576 --> 00:21:32.976 A:middle
Thank you.

